**Code Structure for `run_coworker_periodically.ps1`:**

```powershell
# ... existing setup ...

# Monitor Log File
$monitorLog = Join-Path $repoRoot "coworker_monitor.log"

while ($true) {
    # ... check for tasks ...

    if ($Running) {
        # ...
    } else {
        # Start coworker
        Write-Host "Starting coworker..."
        $process = Start-Process -FilePath "pwsh" -ArgumentList "-File", $ScriptPath -RedirectStandardOutput $monitorLog -PassThru -NoNewWindow

        # Monitor loop
        $history = @() # List of objects { Time, Actions, Lines }
        $startTime = Get-Date

        while ($process.HasExited -eq $false) {
            Start-Sleep -Seconds 30

            if (Test-Path $monitorLog) {
                $content = Get-Content $monitorLog -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
                # Note: Get-Content might lock or be slow on huge files.
                # Optimization: Read only end? No, we need total counts.
                # For infinite loop, file can grow large.
                # "count(\n)" implies total lines.

                $lines = $content.Count
                if ($lines -eq 0) { continue }

                $actions = ($content | Select-String "● ").Count

                $currentStatus = [PSCustomObject]@{
                    Time = Get-Date
                    Lines = $lines
                    Actions = $actions
                }
                $history += $currentStatus

                # Check condition: 3 minutes window
                # Filter history for items > 3 mins ago
                $threeMinsAgo = (Get-Date).AddMinutes(-3)
                $oldStatuses = $history | Where-Object { $_.Time -lt $threeMinsAgo }

                if ($oldStatuses) {
                   $old = $oldStatuses[-1] # closest to 3 mins ago boundary (or oldest kept)

                   # "Infinite loop" definition:
                   # 1. Output is growing ($lines > $old.Lines)
                   # 2. No new actions ($actions == $old.Actions)

                   if ($lines -gt ($old.Lines + 50) -and $actions -eq $old.Actions) {
                       Write-Host "Infinite loop detected! Aborting..."
                       Stop-Process -Id $process.Id -Force

                       # Move tasks from 2working to 3_5aborted
                       # ...
                       break
                   }
                }

                # Prune history (keep last 5 mins)
                $history = $history | Where-Object { $_.Time -gt (Get-Date).AddMinutes(-5) }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Wait**, `Get-Content` on a growing file being written by another process can be tricky in Windows (file locking). `Start-Process -RedirectStandardOutput` locks the file for exclusive write usually?
No, PowerShell redirection usually allows read sharing. But valid concern.
Alternative: `Start-Job` returns output via `Receive-Job`. This is memory-safe(r) if we clear it, but we need *cumulative* counts.
If I `Receive-Job -Keep`, I have the whole history in memory.
If I `Receive-Job` (no keep), I get chunks. I can maintain cumulative counters.
`$totalLines += $chunk.Count`
`$totalActions += ($chunk | Select-String "● ").Count`

This is much better! No file locking issues, no disk I/O for logs.

**Refined PowerShell Logic using Jobs:**

```powershell
    else {
        Write-Host "Starting coworker..."
        $job = Start-Job -FilePath $ScriptPath

        $totalLines = 0
        $totalActions = 0
        $history = @()

        while ($job.State -eq 'Running') {
            Start-Sleep -Seconds 30

            # Receive new output
            $newOutput = Receive-Job -Job $job
            if ($newOutput) {
                # $newOutput is array of strings (lines) or objects
                $newLinesCount = $newOutput.Count
                $newActionsCount = ($newOutput | Select-String "● ").Count

                $totalLines += $newLinesCount
                $totalActions += $newActionsCount

                # Also echo to host so we can see it?
                $newOutput | Write-Host
            }

            $currentStatus = [PSCustomObject]@{
                Time = Get-Date
                Lines = $totalLines
                Actions = $totalActions
            }
            $history += $currentStatus

            # Check 3 min condition
            $threeMinsAgo = (Get-Date).AddMinutes(-3)
            $oldPoint = $history | Where-Object { $_.Time -le $threeMinsAgo } | Select-Object -Last 1

            if ($oldPoint) {
                 # Criterion: Lines grew, Actions didn't
                 if ($totalLines -gt ($oldPoint.Lines + 20) -and $totalActions -eq $oldPoint.Actions) {
                      Write-Warning "Coworker infinite loop detected! (Lines: $totalLines, Actions: $totalActions vs Old: $($oldPoint.Lines), $($oldPoint.Actions))"
                      Stop-Job -Job $job
                      Remove-Job -Job $job -Force

                      # Move task
                      $workingDir = Join-Path $repoRoot "coworker\tasks\2working"
                      $abortedDir = Join-Path $repoRoot "coworker\tasks\3_5aborted"
                      if (!(Test-Path $abortedDir)) { New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path $abortedDir }

                      Get-ChildItem $workingDir -File | ForEach-Object {
                          Write-Warning "Aborting task: $($_.Name)"
                          Move-Item $_.FullName $abortedDir -Force
                      }
                      break
                 }
            }

             # Prune history
            $history = $history | Where-Object { $_.Time -gt (Get-Date).AddMinutes(-10) }
        }

        # Ensure job is removed if it finished normally
        Receive-Job -Job $job | Write-Host
        Remove-Job -Job $job -Force
    }
```

One detail: `Start-Job` runs in a separate PowerShell process. `coworker.ps1` relies on current working directory?
`coworker.ps1` does `Set-Location $repoRoot`. It should be fine.

